│ stop({"edit_points": [[1954, 1966,                                            │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.          │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is an assertion failure in                │
│ SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup():\n  removed instruction should only be used by │
│ instructions inserted during expansion.\nThis asserts that every user of any  │
│ instruction being removed by the SCEVExpanderCleaner must also have been      │
│ recorded as an inserted instruction by that same SCEVExpander. In the         │
│ reproducer, loop-vectorize creates a temporary SCEV check block, expands a    │
│ SCEV predicate into it (producing some instructions), then \"unhooks\" the    │
│ block by moving its original terminator (a BranchInst) into the loop          │
│ preheader to allow cost modeling without affecting normal CFG execution.      │
│ Later, when cleaning up (because vectorization was not performed), the        │
│ SCEVExpanderCleaner attempts to erase the expanded instructions. However,     │
│ their user (the moved branch) was not marked as an inserted instruction,      │
│ since it was an existing instruction relocated rather than created via        │
│ IRBuilder.\nTherefore the invariant expected by the cleanup routine is        │
│ violated and the assertion fires.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nScalarEvolution │
│ prints normal data; nothing suspicious in SCEV expressions. The failure       │
│ happens immediately at the first transformation cleanup point during the      │
│ destruction of GeneratedRTChecks. No earlier IR mutation inside               │
│ loop-vectorize produced invalid SCEV; instead the structural manipulation of  │
│ the runtime check blocks caused a logical mismatch in tracking inserted       │
│ instructions. The SCEVCheckCond was i1 false (debug dump) which means the     │
│ predicate expansion probably produced either constant false or trivial        │
│ instructions; nevertheless the block creation and terminator movement         │
│ executed. Since SCEVCheckCond remained non-null (we never called              │
│ emitSCEVChecks because vectorization wasn't committed), the destructor        │
│ treated the result as unused and attempted cleanup. Users of inserted         │
│ instructions included the moved branch now residing in the Preheader and not  │
│ recorded in the expander.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn                      │
│ GeneratedRTChecks::create(), after generating the SCEVCheckBlock and          │
│ expanding SCEVCheckCond, the code unhooks the block by:\n                     │
│ SCEVCheckBlock->getTerminator()->moveBefore(Preheader->getTerminator()->getIt │
│ erator());\n  new UnreachableInst(..., SCEVCheckBlock);\nThis moves the       │
│ original terminator (branch) into the Preheader. That terminator still uses   │
│ the values (instructions) created during SCEV expansion, but because it was   │
│ not created via the SCEVExpander's IRBuilder callback, it was never           │
│ registered (rememberInstruction) inside SCEVExpander. Consequently, during    │
│ SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup(), the inserted instructions have a user (the    │
│ moved terminator) that is not itself in the inserted set, triggering the      │
│ assertion.\nThe assumption in cleanup() that all users are expander-inserted  │
│ is valid; the vectorizer code violates it by relocating an existing user      │
│ outside the inserted set without marking it.\n\n4. Proposed Edit              │
│ Points:\nEdit LoopVectorize.cpp in GeneratedRTChecks::create(). Before moving │
│ the terminator(s), capture the pointer to the terminator and after moving it, │
│ explicitly register it with the corresponding SCEVExpander via                │
│ rememberInstruction(). Do this for both SCEVCheckBlock and                    │
│ MemCheckBlock.\nThis ensures that any existing instructions moved out (and    │
│ still using expanded values) are recorded as inserted, satisfying the         │
│ invariant in SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup().\nLines 1954-1966 in              │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp (based on provided snippet)   │
│ should be modified to:\n- Store the original terminator(s) before move.\n-    │
│ After moveBefore(), call SCEVExp.rememberInstruction(OldTerm) and             │
│ MemCheckExp.rememberInstruction(OldMemTerm).\n\nDetailed patch intention      │
│ (conceptual):\nBefore:\n  if (SCEVCheckBlock) {\n                             │
│ SCEVCheckBlock->getTerminator()->moveBefore(...);\n    new                    │
│ UnreachableInst(..., SCEVCheckBlock);\n                                       │
│ Preheader->getTerminator()->eraseFromParent();\n  }\nAfter:\n  if             │
│ (SCEVCheckBlock) {\n    Instruction *OldTerm =                                │
│ SCEVCheckBlock->getTerminator();\n    OldTerm->moveBefore(...);\n             │
│ SCEVExp.rememberInstruction(OldTerm);\n    new UnreachableInst(...,           │
│ SCEVCheckBlock);\n    Preheader->getTerminator()->eraseFromParent();\n        │
│ }\nAnalogous for MemCheckBlock.\n\nThis preserves semantics while maintaining │
│ SCEVExpander invariants. Alternative approaches (e.g., cloning instead of     │
│ moving, or marking result used) either leave dead blocks or prevent cleanup   │
│ and leak instructions; registering the moved terminator is the minimal        │
│ consistent fix.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy registering the moved terminators with  │
│ the SCEVExpander, we align the vectorizer's block manipulation with           │
│ SCEVExpanderCleaner's expectations. This fixes the assertion by ensuring that │
│ all users of instructions slated for removal are themselves recognized as     │
│ inserted, preventing the mismatch and crash. The transformation remains       │
│ functionally identical, and cleanup proceeds safely.\n"})                     │
