│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ The crash is an assertion failure in SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup():          │
│   removed instruction should only be used by instructions inserted during     │
│ expansion.                                                                    │
│ This asserts that every user of any instruction being removed by the          │
│ SCEVExpanderCleaner must also have been recorded as an inserted instruction   │
│ by that same SCEVExpander. In the reproducer, loop-vectorize creates a        │
│ temporary SCEV check block, expands a SCEV predicate into it (producing some  │
│ instructions), then "unhooks" the block by moving its original terminator (a  │
│ BranchInst) into the loop preheader to allow cost modeling without affecting  │
│ normal CFG execution. Later, when cleaning up (because vectorization was not  │
│ performed), the SCEVExpanderCleaner attempts to erase the expanded            │
│ instructions. However, their user (the moved branch) was not marked as an     │
│ inserted instruction, since it was an existing instruction relocated rather   │
│ than created via IRBuilder.                                                   │
│ Therefore the invariant expected by the cleanup routine is violated and the   │
│ assertion fires.                                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ ScalarEvolution prints normal data; nothing suspicious in SCEV expressions.   │
│ The failure happens immediately at the first transformation cleanup point     │
│ during the destruction of GeneratedRTChecks. No earlier IR mutation inside    │
│ loop-vectorize produced invalid SCEV; instead the structural manipulation of  │
│ the runtime check blocks caused a logical mismatch in tracking inserted       │
│ instructions. The SCEVCheckCond was i1 false (debug dump) which means the     │
│ predicate expansion probably produced either constant false or trivial        │
│ instructions; nevertheless the block creation and terminator movement         │
│ executed. Since SCEVCheckCond remained non-null (we never called              │
│ emitSCEVChecks because vectorization wasn't committed), the destructor        │
│ treated the result as unused and attempted cleanup. Users of inserted         │
│ instructions included the moved branch now residing in the Preheader and not  │
│ recorded in the expander.                                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ In GeneratedRTChecks::create(), after generating the SCEVCheckBlock and       │
│ expanding SCEVCheckCond, the code unhooks the block by:                       │
│   SCEVCheckBlock->getTerminator()->moveBefore(Preheader->getTerminator()->get │
│ Iterator());                                                                  │
│   new UnreachableInst(..., SCEVCheckBlock);                                   │
│ This moves the original terminator (branch) into the Preheader. That          │
│ terminator still uses the values (instructions) created during SCEV           │
│ expansion, but because it was not created via the SCEVExpander's IRBuilder    │
│ callback, it was never registered (rememberInstruction) inside SCEVExpander.  │
│ Consequently, during SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup(), the inserted             │
│ instructions have a user (the moved terminator) that is not itself in the     │
│ inserted set, triggering the assertion.                                       │
│ The assumption in cleanup() that all users are expander-inserted is valid;    │
│ the vectorizer code violates it by relocating an existing user outside the    │
│ inserted set without marking it.                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Points:                                                      │
│ Edit LoopVectorize.cpp in GeneratedRTChecks::create(). Before moving the      │
│ terminator(s), capture the pointer to the terminator and after moving it,     │
│ explicitly register it with the corresponding SCEVExpander via                │
│ rememberInstruction(). Do this for both SCEVCheckBlock and MemCheckBlock.     │
│ This ensures that any existing instructions moved out (and still using        │
│ expanded values) are recorded as inserted, satisfying the invariant in        │
│ SCEVExpanderCleaner::cleanup().                                               │
│ Lines 1954-1966 in llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp (based on  │
│ provided snippet) should be modified to:                                      │
│ - Store the original terminator(s) before move.                               │
│ - After moveBefore(), call SCEVExp.rememberInstruction(OldTerm) and           │
│ MemCheckExp.rememberInstruction(OldMemTerm).                                  │
│                                                                               │
│ Detailed patch intention (conceptual):                                        │
│ Before:                                                                       │
│   if (SCEVCheckBlock) {                                                       │
│     SCEVCheckBlock->getTerminator()->moveBefore(...);                         │
│     new UnreachableInst(..., SCEVCheckBlock);                                 │
│     Preheader->getTerminator()->eraseFromParent();                            │
│   }                                                                           │
│ After:                                                                        │
│   if (SCEVCheckBlock) {                                                       │
│     Instruction *OldTerm = SCEVCheckBlock->getTerminator();                   │
│     OldTerm->moveBefore(...);                                                 │
│     SCEVExp.rememberInstruction(OldTerm);                                     │
│     new UnreachableInst(..., SCEVCheckBlock);                                 │
│     Preheader->getTerminator()->eraseFromParent();                            │
│   }                                                                           │
│ Analogous for MemCheckBlock.                                                  │
│                                                                               │
│ This preserves semantics while maintaining SCEVExpander invariants.           │
│ Alternative approaches (e.g., cloning instead of moving, or marking result    │
│ used) either leave dead blocks or prevent cleanup and leak instructions;      │
│ registering the moved terminator is the minimal consistent fix.               │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ By registering the moved terminators with the SCEVExpander, we align the      │
│ vectorizer's block manipulation with SCEVExpanderCleaner's expectations. This │
│ fixes the assertion by ensuring that all users of instructions slated for     │
│ removal are themselves recognized as inserted, preventing the mismatch and    │
│ crash. The transformation remains functionally identical, and cleanup         │
│ proceeds safely.                                                              │
│                                                                               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
